Interface IAeManager

All Known Subinterfaces:
IAeAttachmentManager, IAeCoordinationManager, IAeCoordinationManagerInternal, IAeLockManager, IAePersistentProcessManager, IAeProcessManager, IAeQueueManager, IAeRecoverableProcessManager, IAeRecoveryProcessManager, IAeRecoveryQueueManager
All Known Implementing Classes:
AeAbstractAttachmentManager, AeAbstractLockManager, AeAbstractProcessManager, AeBaseQueueManager, AeCoordinationManager, AeDelegatingManager, AeDelegatingPersistentProcessManager, AeDelegatingProcessManager, AeInMemoryProcessManager, AeManagerAdapter, AeMirroringProcessManager, AePersistentProcessManager, AeRecoveryLockManager, AeRecoveryProcessManager, AeRecoveryQueueManager, AeRepeatingProcessManager
public interface IAeManager

Defines the methods that a manager must implement. The application architecture makes use of managers to implement various pieces of the BPEL engine. By isolating the logic in these various implementations (e.g. IAeQueueManager, IAeAlarmManager ...etc) we're able to provide different implmentations without affecting the engine code proper.

stop

public void stop()
Stops the manager. It may be restarted or destroyed from this point. Note that this method may be called by the engine even though a corresponding start method has not yet been called. This can happen when some other manager fails to start.

destroy

public void destroy()
Destroys this instance of the manager. The manager should perform whatever cleanup work is necessary to shut down.
